"We consider pseudorandom generators in which each output bit depends on a constant number of input bits. Such generators have appealingly simple structure: They can be described by a sparse input---output dependency graph $$G$$G and a small predicate $$P$$P that is applied at each output. Following the works of Cryan and Miltersen (MFCS'01) and by Mossel et al (STOC'03), we ask: which graphs and predicates yield \"small-bias\" generators (that fool linear distinguishers)? We identify an explicit class of degenerate predicates and prove the following. For most graphs, all non-degenerate predicates yield small-bias generators, $$f:\\{0,1\\}
